abstract: WASHINGTON — The new Democratic majority in Congress is divided over how to assert its power in opposing the plan by President George W. Bush to send more troops to Baghdad, as leaders explore ways to block financing for a military expansion without being accused of abandoning American forces already in Iraq.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The new Democratic majority in Congress is divided over how to assert its power in opposing the plan by President George W. Bush to send more troops to Baghdad, as leaders explore ways to block financing for a military expansion without being accused of abandoning American forces already in Iraq.
headline_main: Democrats split on how to rein in Bush on troop buildup - Americas - International Herald Tribune
